# QA Bug Validation Agent — Setup & Configuration Guide

This guide walks you through configuring the MCP servers required to run the QA Bug Validation Agent. Complete all sections before running the agent.

---

## Before You Begin — Project Environment Setup

Before configuring any MCP, take a moment to document your project's environments. The agent will reference these during every validation run to ensure it tests the right URLs in the right order.

Fill in the details for your project below:

### Environment URLs

| Environment | Base URL | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| DEV | `https://dev.your-app.com` | Lowest environment — first validation stop |
| QA | `https://qa.your-app.com` | |
| Staging / UAT | `https://staging.your-app.com` | |
| Production | `https://your-app.com` | Highest environment |

> Update the table above with your actual URLs. Add or remove rows to match the environments your project uses (e.g., some projects have a `Preprod` or `SIT` environment).

### Environment Validation Order

When a bug is found in a higher environment, the agent validates from the **lowest affected environment upward**. Define your order here:

```
Validation Order: DEV → QA → Staging → Production
```

Update this to reflect your project's actual promotion pipeline.

### Authentication Per Environment

Different environments often use different credentials or tokens. Note them here so you have them ready when the agent asks:

| Environment | Auth Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| DEV | e.g., Basic Auth / Bearer Token | e.g., shared team credentials |
| QA | | |
| Staging / UAT | | |
| Production | | |

> ⚠️ Never commit real credentials or tokens to version control. Use a secrets manager or a local `.env` file that is listed in `.gitignore`.

---

## Prerequisites

- [Cursor IDE](https://www.cursor.com/) installed
- Node.js v18 or above
- A Jira account with API access
- A Postman account with API access
- Access to the environments you intend to test against

---

## MCP Servers Required

| MCP Server | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Jira MCP | Fetch ticket details, transition status, post comments |
| Playwright MCP | Browser automation — navigation, clicks, screenshots |
| Postman MCP | Fetch API collections and execute requests |

---

## 1. Jira MCP Setup

### Step 1: Get your Jira API Token

1. Log in to your Atlassian account at [https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens](https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens)
2. Click **Create API token**
3. Give it a label (e.g., `QA Agent`) and click **Create**
4. **Copy the token immediately** — you won't be able to see it again

### Step 2: Find your Jira Base URL

This is the root URL of your Jira workspace, for example:
```
https://your-org.atlassian.net
```

### Step 3: Add Jira MCP to Cursor

Open your Cursor MCP configuration file:
- **Mac/Linux**: `~/.cursor/mcp.json`
- **Windows**: `%APPDATA%\Cursor\mcp.json`

Add the following entry inside the `mcpServers` object:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "jira": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@smithery/cli@latest", "run", "@readysetcloud/jira-mcp", "--config", "{}"],
      "env": {
        "JIRA_BASE_URL": "https://your-org.atlassian.net",
        "JIRA_EMAIL": "your-email@example.com",
        "JIRA_API_TOKEN": "your-api-token-here"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Replace `JIRA_BASE_URL`, `JIRA_EMAIL`, and `JIRA_API_TOKEN` with your actual values.

### Step 4: Verify

Restart Cursor and check that the Jira MCP appears as connected in the MCP panel.

---

## 2. Playwright MCP Setup

### Step 1: Add Playwright MCP to Cursor

In the same `mcp.json` file, add the following entry alongside your Jira config:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "jira": { ... },
    "playwright": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@executeautomation/playwright-mcp-server"]
    }
  }
}
```

No API token is required — Playwright MCP runs locally and controls a browser on your machine.

### Step 2: Screenshot Folder

The agent will automatically create a screenshots folder at the path below when UI validation begins:

```
/screenshots/[JIRA_TICKET_ID]/
```

Make sure the directory where you run Cursor has write permissions. You can also pre-create this folder manually if preferred:

```bash
mkdir -p screenshots
```

### Step 3: Verify

Restart Cursor. The Playwright MCP should appear as connected. You can do a quick sanity check by asking the agent to navigate to any public URL and take a screenshot.

---

## 3. Postman MCP Setup

> 📋 **Note:** Documentation for Postman MCP setup will be added here. Steps to be provided separately.

---

## Full `mcp.json` Example

Once all three MCPs are configured, your `mcp.json` should look like this:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "jira": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@smithery/cli@latest", "run", "@readysetcloud/jira-mcp", "--config", "{}"],
      "env": {
        "JIRA_BASE_URL": "https://your-org.atlassian.net",
        "JIRA_EMAIL": "your-email@example.com",
        "JIRA_API_TOKEN": "your-api-token-here"
      }
    },
    "playwright": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@executeautomation/playwright-mcp-server"]
    },
    "postman": {
      "...": "configuration to be added"
    }
  }
}
```

---

## Troubleshooting

| Issue | Fix |
|---|---|
| Jira MCP not connecting | Double-check `JIRA_BASE_URL` format — must include `https://` and no trailing slash |
| API token rejected | Regenerate the token from Atlassian and update `mcp.json` |
| Playwright MCP not launching | Ensure Node.js v18+ is installed — run `node -v` to check |
| Screenshots not saving | Check write permissions on the working directory |
| Postman MCP not connecting | Refer to the Postman setup section once it is documented |

---

## Next Steps

Once all MCPs are configured and verified:

1. Ensure project rules are loaded: the agent's **primary behaviour** is defined in `cursor/rules/01-jira-orchestrator.mdc` (always applied). UI and API detail lives in `02-ui-validation.mdc` and `03-api-validation.mdc`.
2. Open Cursor and start a new chat with the QA Bug Validation Agent
3. Provide a Jira Ticket ID to begin
4. The agent will run the orchestrated flow — fetch the ticket, transition to **QA In Progress** when your workflow allows it, classify the bug, confirm plans with you, validate via MCPs, then draft/post the Jira comment and optional final transition

For behaviour or phase changes, edit `cursor/rules/01-jira-orchestrator.mdc` first.